# Step 3: Check missing values in the dataset
print("--- Checking for Missing Values ---")
missing_values = df.isnull().sum()
missing_percentage = (df.isnull().sum() / len(df)) * 100
missing_df = pd.DataFrame({'Missing Count': missing_values, 'Percentage': missing_percentage})
print(missing_df[missing_df['Missing Count'] > 0]) # Only print columns that have missing values

if missing_df['Missing Count'].sum() == 0:
    print("\nNo missing values found in the dataset. Data is clean!")
else:
    print("\nMissing values found. Review the report above to decide on imputation strategies.")
    # If you find missing values, you would add imputation code here.

plt.ylabel('Count')

# Step 6: Check if the number of premium charges for smokers or non-smokers is increasing as they are aging
# Using lmplot to visualize the relationship with separate regression lines for smoker/non-smoker
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7)) # Adjusting initial figure size, lmplot creates its own figure
sns.lmplot(x='age', y='charges', hue='smoker', data=df,
           height=7, aspect=1.3, ci=95,  # ci=95 shows 95% confidence interval
           scatter_kws={'alpha':0.6, 's': 40}, line_kws={'lw':2})
plt.title('Premium Charges vs. Age Differentiated by Smoker Status', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Age', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Premium Charges', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6) # Add a grid for better readability
plt.tight_layout() # Adjust layout
plt.show()
